<div style="font-family:'Pacifico',sans-serif;background:-webkit-linear-gradient(90deg,#F3722C,#F94144);color:#d3d3d3;border:3px solid #ffffff;padding:5px 10px;margin:1em;text-align:center;"><font size="6">Overview</font></div></center></center>
{{Blurimage|file=Sunrise-and-set.png|caption=A famous image.}}
Level 629 unfolds as an endless, tropical coastal level divided into distinct variations of Environment, including Suburbia, The Amusement Region and the Coast.
{{Blurimage|file=Level9915Building.webp|250px|caption=An outside building in Level 629.}}
The entire environment remains firmly anchored in the mid-century modern architectural style and cultural atmosphere of mid-1960s to early 1970s America.
Every town, street layout, and coastal boardwalk feels remarkably natural and free of the structural glitches common in other levels.

However, the most strange anomaly of the level is its temporal lock.
Every time a wanderer enters, the date resets precisely to Saturday, October 27th, 1962—the absolute climax and most dangerous day of the Cuban Missile Crisis, a tension visually reinforced by the ominous air-raid sirens scattered across the horizon.
{{Blurimage|file=Level9915GasStation.webp|caption=Crimson Sky.}}
The sky has purple, pinkish-red, red and orange hues, with other colors being fairly present. The environment is darkened, and is fairly illuminated by streetlights, these who falls, injuring any unsuspecting individual.
The lights inside households are weak, lasting only a few minutes before a streetlight falls somewhere nearby. Garages may be the only source of safety in Level 629, having foods inside the trash cans on their corners, and speakers, those who are not working, but if repaired, they will play a non-stop version of "Back There, Benjamin" by The Caretaker.

As said before, Level 629 is in a constant loop of sunrises and sunsets, both lasting almost exactly fifteen minutes each, never truly reaching a full state of day or night before looping once more. The level contains a swiftly moving sun and moon, strangely appearing to be similar in distance to the ground of the level. Due to the level commonly being in a state of darkness and the cold temperatures of the level, bringing heat sources and lights are highly recommended.
Swaying palm trees and coastal grasses dots the landscape. The temperature of Level 629 is between 16°C to 21°C, although the climate may feel cooler due to natural winds.

Despite its timeline, Level 629 possesses modern technology in the form of electronic devices such as mobile phones, computers, and smart televisions. However, these machines are depleted of their internal components, sometimes also exhibiting signs of disrepair as evidenced by missing chunks and general instability of the technology, it is known that it was left behind by old wanderers.
The level shifts its appearance for each person based on their own notions of 1960s nostalgia. If two people enter through a door together, they will instantly split into parallel visual dimensions of the same space.
The most lethal environmental hazard of Level 629 comes from the mechanical network of Chrysler Air Raid Sirens scattered across the rooftops of Downtown and platforms near the Coast. These sirens do not require electricity or fuel to operate, they trigger autonomously when the sky shifts into a deep, blood-red hue.

An interesting constant between many of the houses of Level 629 is the presence of various weapons, often well maintained. These weapons range from lightweight hunting knives to polymer rifle platforms. The source of these weapons is unknown, although their presence has alerted interest from many attempting to scavenge the level for arms.
Deeply tied to the 1962 atmosphere, numerous underground fallout bunkers can be found hidden beneath the backyard lawns of Suburbia and inside the concrete foundations of Downtown. These structures serve as the only reliable safe zones within the level.
Visual anomalies may be found over time; these anomalies only appear if the wanderer begins to experience the psychological problems that household furniture causes in humans<ref>Often Called Phenomenon 629, or Loremdamnum</ref>. Wanderers reported that the most common anomalies are:
*Objects and houses floating.
*Hallucinations, audits, and extreme visual disturbances.
**Steps, hard breathing, and heartbeats.
*Déjà vú.
*Extremely dilapidated houses.
*Poles falling more frequently
*Rapid loss of sanity.
*Lights normally on.
*Houses with more or less floors.

<div style="text-align:center"></div><div style="font-family:'Pacifico',sans-serif;background:-webkit-linear-gradient(90deg,#F3722C,#F94144);color:#d3d3d3;border:3px solid #ffffff;padding:5px 10px;margin:1em;text-align:center;"><font size="6">Structures</font></div>
{{Blurimage|file=Level629Home.jpg|caption=A interior of one of '''Level 629''' houses.}}
The structures are entirely constructed in a 1960s Western architectural design, influenced by American culture. These buildings are physically pristine, showing no structural glitches or signs of decay, which creates a deceptive sense of realism.
Local diners, shops, and houses are fully functional and perpetually stocked with fresh food and supplies that never spoil. Inside the residential homes, typical American breakfasts sit on tables and vintage television sets remain active, constantly buzzing with static.

The primary anomaly of these structures is their spatial isolation. The interior and exterior layouts shift appearance for each entrant based on their individual notions of nostalgia. If multiple people enter a structure together, they instantly split into parallel visual dimensions of the same space, making physical contact or communication impossible.

Furthermore, the concrete walls of the taller commercial buildings act as a hazardous acoustic echo chamber. When the sirens activate, the architecture amplifies the sound waves, causing immediate hearing damage and accelerating psychological breakdown.

Deep beneath the lawns and concrete foundations of these structures lie heavy, reinforced Cold War fallout bunkers. These lead-lined basements are the only areas dense enough to completely block out the destructive frequency of the sirens, serving as the primary safe zones within the level.

The doors and windows of the structures exhibit a high resistance to physical force. While they can be opened normally from the inside or outside, attempting to breach a locked structure or break the glass panes using external tools is impossible. The materials absorb the impact completely without sustaining damage, forcing travelers to search for open entry points.
The electrical grids within the buildings operate on a closed, self-sustaining loop. Outlets and light fixtures provide a constant flow of power despite the lack of external power plants or visible wiring grids. However, connecting any modern technology or electronic devices from outside the Backrooms into these outlets will instantly short-circuit the device, rendering it permanently non-functional.

<div style="text-align:center"></div><div style="font-family:'Pacifico',sans-serif;background:-webkit-linear-gradient(90deg,#F3722C,#F94144);color:#d3d3d3;border:3px solid #ffffff;padding:5px 10px;margin:1em;text-align:center;"><font size="6">The Biomes</font></div>
<div class="tabs vertical">
<ul class="tabs__caption">
<li class="active">Suburbia</li>
<li>Coast</li>
</ul>

<div class="tabs__content active">
===<span style="font-family:'Pacifico';">SUBURBIA</span>===
{{Underline|FD5E53}}
{{Blurimage|file=SaturatedSkies.gif|caption=A footage of Level 629's suburbs.}}
Brick office buildings and drive-in diners slowly give way to identical houses with neat lawns and white fences. Everything looks exactly like a clean American neighborhood from 1962.

Vintage cars sit empty by the curbs. Inside the homes, tables are set with fresh breakfast foods, and televisions buzz with static.
This realistic setting is psychologically exhausting, as it constantly reminds travelers of a normal world they cannot reach.
This area is dangerous despite its peaceful appearance.

Skin-Stealers hide inside the empty houses, mimicking familiar voices to trick lonely survivors into entering. 
The design of the Suburbs is somewhat more labyrinthine compared to the conventional appearance of Level 629, which normalizes a human-like facade, albeit not to the extent of being bizarre.

It comprises of repeating, grid-like thoroughfares that are virtually indistinguishable from cities within the Frontrooms; however, the trajectory within the level causes the repetition of the environment to be imperceptible, owing to the configuration of the edifices.
</div>

<div class="tabs__content">
===<span style="font-family:'Pacifico';">COAST</span>===
{{Underline|FD5E53}}
{{Blurimage|file=629.1.webp|caption=Beach.}}
The Coast marks the outer edge of Level 629, both in geography and in mind. It stretches out as an endless beach of white sand, lined with tropical palm trees. Yet, the air is completely dead. No wind blows, and the leaves never move, making the whole paradise feel fake.
The ocean itself is an eerie sight. The water is perfectly flat and motionless, acting like a giant mirror that reflects the pink and purple hues of the sky. There are no waves and no sound of tides. Stealing a glance at the open water feels wrong, as the absolute silence weighs heavily on anyone standing near the shore.
Staring at the horizon triggers a deep, historic dread. Because of the 1962 atmosphere, travelers often experience a sudden wave of panic, becoming convinced that military warships or missile trails are appearing in the distance. This visual trick feeds the paranoia of the level, forcing people to run back inland.
Vintage wooden speedboats and yachts from the sixties sit anchored by empty piers or left stranded on the sand. Their engines are intact, but starting them up is a massive gamble, as the noise instantly alerts whatever is hiding nearby.
There may be numerous markets beyond the shore itself, but they can only be accessed through the mentioned segments due to the steep altitude difference that divides the shore from the upper part of the environment.
Supplies within the Coast are heavily scarce and difficult to discover, with the only visible stocks of food present within the markets, which are only rarely visited due to the difficult nature of entering their area. 

</div>

</div>

<div style="text-align:center"></div><div style="font-family:'Pacifico',sans-serif;background:-webkit-linear-gradient(90deg,#F3722C,#F94144);color:#d3d3d3;border:3px solid #ffffff;padding:5px 10px;margin:1em;text-align:center;"><font size="6">Entities</font></div>
